05441nam a22010815i 9781400887873DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20172018nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008878737 a10.1515/97814008878732doi  a(DE-B1597)490446  a(OCoLC)998784938  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aPR6001.U4 7aLIT0140002bisacsh04a821.914223  aHM 1655qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/50883:118521 aCostello, Bonnie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Plural of Us :bPoetry and Community in Auden and Others /cBonnie Costello. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2017] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b1 halftone.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Speaking of Us -- t2. The Demagogue and the Sotto Voce -- t3. Song of My Selves -- t4. Private Stuff and Public Spirit -- t5. Tribes and Ambiguities -- t6. Poet and Audience -- t7. Crowds, Publics, Congregations -- t8. Invitations to the Common -- t9. The Future of Us -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Plural of Us is the first book to focus on the poet’s use of the first-person plural voice—poetry’s “we.” Closely exploring the work of W. H. Auden, Bonnie Costello uncovers the trove of thought and feeling carried in this small word. While lyric has long been associated with inwardness and a voice saying “I,” “we” has hardly been noticed, even though it has appeared throughout the history of poetry. Reading for this pronoun in its variety and ambiguity, Costello explores the communal function of poetry—the reasons, risks, and rewards of the first-person plural.Costello adopts a taxonomic approach to her subject, considering “we” from its most constricted to its fully unbounded forms. She also takes a historical perspective, following Auden’s interest in the full range of “the human pluralities” in a time of particular pressure for and against the collective. Costello offers new readings as she tracks his changing approach to voice in democracy. Examples from many other poets—including Walt Whitman, T. S. Eliot, Elizabeth Bishop, and Wallace Stevens—arise throughout the book, and the final chapter offers a consideration of how contemporary writers find form for what George Oppen called “the meaning of being numerous.”Connecting insights to philosophy of language and to recent work in concepts of community, The Plural of Us shows how poetry raises vital questions—literary and social—about how we speak of our togetherness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aPoetryxCriticism and interpretation. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh  aElizabeth Bishop.  aGeorge Oppen.  aLaw Like Love.  aMontaigne.  aPlato.  aT. S. Eliot.  aThe Orators.  aW. H. Auden.  aWallace Stevens.  aWalt Whitman.  aambiguity.  aaudience relationship.  acommon.  acrowds.  afirst-person plural.  agroup identity.  alove poems.  alove poetry.  aperformers.  aphilosophy of language.  aplurality.  apoems.  apoet.  apoetic audience.  apoetry.  apoets.  apronouns.  aself.  asocial thought.  atogetherness.  auniversals.  awe.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311054332208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106065910 cprintz978069117281140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400887873?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400887873423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781400887873/original  a978-3-11-054332-2  Princeton University Pres